                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                    8 schools   to vie for honours  Calcutta: Eight top schools of the city will vie for glory in the Inter-School Twenty20 championship, which kicks off on Thursday.  The eight schools mdash; St Xavier rsquo;s Collegiate School, National High for Boys School, Don Bosco (Park Circus), Assembly of God Church School, Lakshmipat Singhania Academy, Calcutta Boys rsquo; School, La Martiniere for Boys and Pailan World School mdash; have been divided into two groups.  Two schools from each group will advance to the semi-finals. The tournament will be played in the shortest format of the game over 10 days and the final will be held on January 17. The Twenty20 tournament is sponsored by Cheetos, Boost, Nutrine, Reebok, Dabur and TTIS among others and organised by Mindscapes Maestros.  PCB tussle  Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has got entangled into a tussle with their own legal advisor Tafazzul Rizvi who has demanded an apology from a senior official for issuing him a show cause notice. Rizvi made a statement after the PCB delayed submitting documents and other evidences to prove Shoaib Akhtar rsquo;s past disciplinary record as directed by the court following the pacer rsquo;s writ petition in the Lahore High Court.  Miandad rsquo;s role  Karachi: Former Pakistan captain Javed Miandad, has taken to task of the chief curator of the PCB for rolling out poor pitches at some of the venues in the Quaid-e-Azam trophy.  Players fined  Dubai: Bangladesh captain Mohammed Ashraful and wicketkeeper Mushfiqur Rahim were on Wednesday fined for excessive and aggressive appealing during the third day rsquo;s play in the second Test against Sri Lanka in Chittagong.   Bhutia misses  New Delhi: India football captain Bhaichung Bhutia could not make it to the top 10 finalists after being nominated among the 43 footballers for the Asian Footballer of the Year award instituted by a pan-Arab Abu Dhabi soccer weekly rsquo;.  Saina advances  Kuala Lumpur: Saina Nehwal beat German Nicole Grether 21-15, 21-8 in the Round I of the Malaysian Super Series on Wednesday.   Germany win  Sydney: Germany won a tie-breaker in the deciding mixed doubles to knock the US out of the Hopman Cup in Perth on Wednesday. Nicolas Kiefer and Sabine Lisicki beat James Blake and M. Shaughnessy 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 and secure a 2-1 win.  Khushi best  Calcutta: Bengal rsquo;s Khushi Dharewa emerged champion in the girls rsquo; category of the national under-7 chess tournament that concluded in Nagpur on Wednesday. Khushi had a score of 9.5 after 11 rounds of play. In the boys rsquo; section, Bengal rsquo;s Mitrabha Guha came close to emulating Khushi after he was tied for the first place, but fell short at the last hurdle.  
